This paper focuses on face recognition technology, which is a subfield of computer vision (cs.CV). The study also involves analyzing the accuracy of state-of-the-art face recognition technology for identifying children who may have been victims of child trafficking or abduction, which falls under the category of computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also involves fine-tuning an open-source face recognition matcher, which is a machine learning task and falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The study also involves analyzing the verification and open-set identification accuracies, which are performance metrics in multimedia systems (cs.MM). Finally, the study involves analyzing the performance of face recognition technology for tracing and identifying children, which has implications for human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
